summary_comment: Professor Christa is highly regarded for her exceptional care and support, making her classes exceptionally enjoyable and stress-free. Students appreciate her clear expectations, straightforward teaching style, and focus on wellness beyond academic performance. Professor Newtz similarly garners praise for her dedication to therapeutic communication and creating a supportive learning environment that fosters both academic and personal success.

Ratings.comment: Prof Newtz really cares about therapeutic communication which makes the class so much more enjoyable. It really feels like she cares about whether or not we succeed not just as students but in our careers.

Christa is such a sweet and caring professor. She really makes the students feel comfortable within the college. She is a super easy grader. As long as you turn in your assignments on time, you will get a 100%. Exams are easy and class counts participation. I never used a textbook!

Christa is an amazing professor, very caring. Her class may be easier and not as much information as other semester 1 classes, but it is SOO important for foundational nursing care and thinking. Tests are very straight forward. Highly recommend doing hw when assigned (even though not mandatory) as it will help in later nursing classes/clinicals

Christa is so caring. She makes sure everyone in the class is prioritizing their wellness and looks far beyond simply being an instructor. She often takes time in class for gratitude activities, relaxation techniques, and self-reflection. The class was very straightforward and she was clear on the expectations from the beginning. Amazing!
I loved Christa! She really cares about all of her students and is willing to help whenever she can.
By far the best prof ive ever had.

summary_comment: The professor is generally effective in covering the material, using personal anecdotes to engage students, and providing clear study guides for exams. However, her teaching methods can be somewhat impersonal, with limited interaction and reliance on outdated lecture materials. Her classes can be dry at times, but her humor and practical examples help make the content more approachable.

Ratings.comment: During COVID she reused old lectures that often times had unhelpful and irrelevant information. She did very little to engage with the class, she actually interacted with us I think only three times in the semester, one of those times was after students complained to the dean about her and she had to address it Did not feel like she cared about us.

The material in this class is pretty straightforward, but there is a lot of information covered. There is no attendance grade, but attendance is important because she leaves blanks in her slides. Some of her classes she does recorded lectures instead of in-class, which is nice. Exams aren't hard if you're well prepared.

She is a good professor. She goes over the material in lecture, so it is very important to go to fill out the powerpoint. Uses great examples from her life as a nurse. If you study the study guide for exams you will do well in the class! She is slightly intimidating though!

Stacy is a great professor, very funny and straight forward. She and Hollie really work well together to teach health assessment. Lectures can be a bit bland (learning about assessment techniques and different tests), but her stories and personality make learning the material fun and easy

Dr. Martini is so personable and caring. She is really passionate about what she does and it translates in her lectures. She is great about communicating and is very clear about course expectations and assignment instructions. Definitely one of my favorite college professors I have ever had.

summary_comment: The professor is generally perceived as unengaging and disorganized, with lectures described as boring and difficult to follow, often filled with technical issues and last-minute changes. While she is noted for her caring nature and occasional niceness, students find her class material to be overly extensive and repetitive, with exams being unnecessarily tough on basic concepts and containing errors.

Ratings.comment: Her lectures are very dragged out and boring, can barely hear her at times. This class would have served better if it was asynchronous. She makes her exams unnecessarily tough over easy concepts. Her exams always have some sort of mistake, such as typos or conflicting answer choices. Other than that she's nice.

You could tell that Anita really cares about her students and wants everyone to learn. The class was pretty boring and slow but it was okay. I had her for health assessment lab too and she was an amazing lab instructor.

Taking her class via zoom, which I understand changes things. However, shes extremely unorganized, misspeaks often, is unclear, and changes her mind very often on whether class is asynchronous or synchronous. Often has things in ppt that are no longer used and just goes sorry I should have looked at this before class! Draws classes out.

S T U P I D class. Anita is a nice lady, but gives boring lectures. With that said, she did cry on the second lecture... class felt so awkward. Useless class/ common knowledge. Could have been taught in 3 lectures-was dragged out. Went to first couple then skipped all the rest. Gives extra credit but there is no point bc everything is easy.
A lot of the information in this class is common sense. I tried to go to all of her lectures but had a hard time paying attention. All of the assignments and exams were easy.

She is a very, very nice and caring person, but her lectures were pointless (powerpoints are posted, half the time class is cancelled, homework is extra credit, online exams, no participation). Most of the class doesn't show up to lecture. Exams are fairly easy if you study a few days in advance. She is very sweet though - bless her.

She is very bad at explaining any of the course content. You also have about 2-3 hours worth of lectures to listen to BEFORE class, usually have a quiz (tRAT/iRAT) every class, but you should leave right after because lecture is useless. You'll mainly have to teach yourself and study ALOT

She ensures students thoroughly understand the material through effective communication and regular quizzes that aid in preparation for exams. Ratings.comment: I love Sarah Warren. She was my lecture instructor and she is definitely passionate about teaching. She is very clear and articulate, and makes sure you understand what is being taught. Gives great feedback and is always giving extra credit opportunities. We had quizzes every week and they were very helpful when it came time to study for midterms.
She was my clinical instructor for this course and she was amazing. We had to learn all of our skills over zoom and she managed to make it as good as she could. She also gave really great feedback.

summary_comment: This professor offers a highly unsatisfactory learning experience, with no lectures provided and an overwhelming amount of self-study required from students. The exams are extensive and use Proctorio, while the instructor is difficult to reach and provides unclear feedback on assignments.

Ratings.comment: DO NOT TAKE CLASS WITH THIS PROFESSOR. This was the worst experience I've ever had in college. NO live lectures or recorded lectures, you just have to teach yourself everything by reading the textbook. And then there is one midterm and one final using Proctorio. Both exams cover 30+ chapters. Completely unfair.

Dr. McGhee is barely accessible via carmen; takes forever to respond (if ever). Instruction is horrible. Unclear reasoning when taking off points for answers to questions submitted correctly. I do not recommend taking courses taught by this lecturer.

summary_comment: Sarah is an effective and supportive professor who requires significant effort but is highly recommended. She offers manageable assignments like a broken-down research paper and an oral presentation, and her grading is relatively lenient, especially on the first draft of the research paper. Her classes provide valuable insights into the U.S. healthcare system.

Ratings.comment: Sarah is a great professor for this online course! You definitely have to put in some effort, but she wants her students to succeed and is very helpful. If you do well enough on the first draft of the research paper, you can even choose to not submit a final draft! Easy way to fulfill a GE and learn about disparities in healthcare.

This is by far one of the easiest second-year writing courses to fulfill the GE. There is one long research paper, but it is broken up into parts, which makes writing it very manageable. There are also a few quizzes and discussion posts which are easy, and then an easy Oral Presentation that you record online. Sarah is a great professor, would rec!

This class does require a significant amount of effort. There are two papers for the class; both are very research based. You cannot get by putting in minimal effort, and you have to watch all the lecture videos. However, I think I learned a lot about the US healthcare system through this class, and would recommend it.

Not graded by many things. 2 papers, 2 discussion posts, and 1 oral presentation. Do NOT need books. Weekly lectures with usually two 1 hour long videos- one on writing and one on healthcare. Papers take a good time to write. First rough draft the lowest score she gave was 76, so not the harshest grader. Second paper will def be graded harder.

summary_comment: The professor's teaching quality varies significantly among students. Some find the class challenging due to ambiguous test questions, outdated lecture materials, and delayed releases of course content, while others appreciate her helpfulness and dedication to student success, particularly in preparing them for the NCLEX. Overall, the grading system and availability can be inconsistent, affecting students' understanding and performance.

Ratings.comment: This is an easy nursing class turned difficult. The textbook is useless, the test questions are ambiguous, there are very few points that make up the class, and no assignments are graded on time by the prof. so you don't know where your grade stands in the class.
Discussion boards are long and time consuming. Also worth a huge part of your grade. Exams dont make sense, get ready to defend your answers. Takes forever to get grades back.

Useless material that's terribly taught. Lectures and slides contain errors and outdated information. Exam questions are vague and don't reflect knowledge of the material. Cannot defend exam answers and typically keeps questions that over half the class missed. Presents homeopathic BS therapies as fact. Prepare to be frustrated.

This professor always released lectures late (sometimes a full week late), was never available for questions, and tested students on nitty gritty details of the book rather than on the things that she lectured about. Her lectures were extremely general and brief but the test questions were very in-depth. I taught myself everything from the book.
Dr. Baker is a very nice professor. Her exams are set up to prepare you for the NCLEX. Easy to get a B, very hard to get an A.

Opens course for you to go at your own pace, 3 discussion boards to complete, videos to watch, and a lot of articles to read. No textbook needed for this class. As long as you watch the powerpoint lectures and take a few notes you should do pretty good.
Discussion boards are a must, although they are fairly easy. Use the book and powerpoints for the quizzes. Only read the parts of the book that go with the powerpoints.

Best teacher EVER!!! She was sooooooo helpful, and she wants all her students to be successful. She very compassionate about what she's teaching and love Pediatrics. If you have her as an instructor you’re honored. BE THANKFUL!!!! Have fun.
Best teacher I have ever had in my life
Awesome instrutor!!!! She is knowledgable and awesome

summary_comment: Dr. Bowles is highly regarded for her excellent teaching quality, consistently engaging students and promptly responding to inquiries. She effectively inspires her students to excel, particularly in the field of nursing.

Ratings.comment: Aside from this class being online due to the pandemic, I absolutely loved this course! Dr. Bowles is a wonderful Professor and never hesitates to answer any questions. She also is quick to respond to emails and lets you know when her quizzes and exams will be graded by. Make sure you take good notes and pay attention to lectures.
Dr. Bowles is a wonderful nurse who makes you, in turn, also want to become a wonderful nurse.

Ratings.comment: This was a very interesting class. Prof. O'Brien obviously cared that everyone got full credit. I would take her class again in a heartbeat.

No textbook, but she does assign some reading material which was helpful when finding EBP ideas and research. I never liked my previous nursing EBP classes or projects, but she made it fun!

summary_comment: Dr. Mackos is highly regarded by some students for her clear explanations and engaging teaching style, particularly in making complex pathophysiology topics accessible and enjoyable. However, other students criticize her for being inflexible in accommodating different learning styles and for the disconnect between lecture content and course objectives, citing her as unresponsive to reasonable requests and dismissive of student feedback.

Ratings.comment: In my opinion, Tries to Roadblock student reasonable requests to get better .ppt version of lecture slides. Didn't like Her attitude; seemd she didnt want to accomm diff learning styles w reasonble requests. Saw huge discrepancies betwn lecture content & course objectives; I think there were lame excuses; just clean it up. Rating Mackos poorly.

In my opinion, Tries to Roadblock student reasonable requests to get better .ppt version of lecture slides. Didn't like Her attitude; seemd she didnt want to accomm diff learning styles w reasonble requests. Saw huge discrepancies betwn lecture content & course objectives; I think there were lame excuses; just clean it up.

Dr. Mackos is one of the best teachers I have ever had. She is an amazing explainer, and she really cares about her students. I genuinely enjoy her lectures- she makes pathophysiology super fun and interesting!

Professor Makos is all over the place in lectures She goes off topic a lot She is not specific towards the test at all She will have you do a mid semester survey and dispute everything the class ask of her This is the first class I have taken at the university where I do not feel like the professors goal is to make sure you do well in the course

Dr Mackos is a good professor who has a clear and logical lecture style. She is really easy to follow and understand. She is very caring and responsive. Would definitely take classes she teaches in the future.

One of the best teachers I've ever had. The pathophys content is difficult to digest but Dr. Mackos breaks it down into clear, palatable chunks of information. She is also entertaining and kind. Highly recommend!
Dr. Mackos is an excellent lecturer and clearly knows exactly what shes talking about in regards to pathophysiology. Couldnt praise her teaching skills enough!

This course had a lot of material, and it is very difficult material. Dr. Makos is very nice and was a fine teacher, but her style of teaching did not make this material easier to understand than if I read the book or watched videos online (both of which I had to do).

summary_comment: This professor is widely regarded as having a poor teaching quality, with students finding her class overwhelming due to frequent guest lectures, extensive group projects, and an excessive amount of homework. Quizzes are described as overly difficult and unhelpful, with no feedback provided. While some find the content interesting, the overall experience is marked by frustration over unclear instructions and low exam performance despite significant study efforts.

Ratings.comment: She is a nice person, but her class is just terrible. She brings in guest lectures every week, group projects biweekly and just insane amount of homework. The quizzes are SO hard for no reason and she won't share the answers or justify why the answers are wrong. The quizzes are open note but not on the quiz. Also videos each week are 50+ min long.

Should not be even called a professor. She does NOT teach a thing. Relies on guest speakers to teach and quizzes on niche information from them or videos pulled from the web. All course work is group work. She will not give credit back despite talking to her. She'll just blame you for not following instructions she does not provide.
You will get good grades if you follow the rubrics and the instructions are clear.
This class has interesting. The only grades came from parts of our group project. No quizzes at all.

Absolutely the worst professor I've ever had. In a clinical class, exams account for 80% of our grade and ask questions about statistics and random facts. There are dozens or videos, power points, articles, and links to study before class, usually taking me 5 hours. I spent hours studying for exams and still got a B on every exam. Absolutely awful.

Ratings.comment: The most amazing professor. She will ignite a passion of nursing in your soul, and she genuinely cares about her students. Also- all the chili peppers.

summary_comment: This professor's classes are known for being densely packed with information and highly time-consuming, with many students finding them difficult and requiring extensive out-of-class study. Opinions vary widely; while some praise her extensive knowledge and simplify test questions, others criticize her teaching effectiveness, organization, and lack of depth in explaining pathophysiology.

Ratings.comment: This class has so much information packed into each lecture. A lot of out of class lectures since they never finish what they are supposed to cover in class. Spent way too much time on this class. This course is also ridiculously hard and just really time consuming.

She is super boring and goes through the material way too slow. She ends up not covering half the lecture in class and makes us finish it on our own outside of class. I basically have to teach myself half the material.

Cindy was a great professor. She wrote her own book on pathophysiology so I don't know how some students can say she does not know what she is talking about. She gives a lot of information, and her tests are usually much more simplified than you would expect. Probably could have learned more, but a wonderful, kind, and knowledgeable lady

anderson doesn't know what she is talking about most of the time and contradicts herself quite often, easily one of the most disorganized professors i have ever had. her tests are extremely simple which reflects her own actual knowledge of the subject. i feel as if i am not learning probably one of the most critical foundational areas of nursing.
She didn't really know what she was doing and taught more about the anatomy than the pathophysiology. Her tests were SO easy that you could have not studied and got an A on them.

summary_comment: Professor Nolan's teaching approach is polarizing; while some appreciate his kindness and genuine interest in student learning, many find the class structure inefficient and the assignments unhelpful, perceiving them as busy work rather than meaningful learning experiences.

Ratings.comment: Ok so Professor Nolan might be cool and all, but this class STUNK. The class is all online and there are assignments due every other week, but they are the dumbest assignments Ive ever had to do. The entire, and I mean ENTIRE class is busy work. The class could/should be taught in about 3 lectures. Waste of mine and your time!
Dr. Nolan was very kind and helpful and seemed genuinely interested in helping students learn.

SEI.Subject: NRSPRCT
SEI.Class Name: Doctor of Nursing Practice Professional Seminar

summary_comment: Dr. Kolcun is known for her challenging and demanding teaching style, often requiring extensive preparation and a significant time commitment from students. While some appreciate her care and effort to ensure understanding, others find her approach overly rigorous and frustrating, citing issues with pop quizzes, unfair grading, and the overall structure of the class.

Ratings.comment: She is extremely tough and hard. She talks super fast and tries to make the quizzes hard. Class is very organized and put together. Do not like how you have to watch 3 hours of pre recorded lecture AND then 3 hours of in person lecture. She said this class should take 10 hours of your time outside class.

This is a HARD class but Dr. Kolcun clearly cares about her students. You HAVE to be prepared before you come to class and do NOT fall behind. She is very receptive to feedback and genuinely wants us to succeed.

Med Surg is a really hard class but Dr. Kolcun does a good job of making the content understandable. If you can make time to read the textbook it is really helpful but you don't have to to pass, all of the information you will be tested on is in the PowerPoint slides.

Med Surg is a hard class to begin with, but Dr. Kolcun helps you get through it. She always makes sure the class is understanding the material and allows people to ask many questions. There is a quiz every week over the material learned that day so it is best to prepare for class to do well on these quizzes. Prepare to put in work for a good grade.

She gives 6 pop quizzes throughout the semester. She isnt very empathetic towards students. Gave us an exam over things we havent learned and made it worth 50 points. Wouldnt round my grade up 0.4% to a B-. Very frustrating class.

Kaitlyn is a very energetic teacher and cares about the subject. There were 6 pop quizzes and class had a lot of time just sitting around (3 hour class). HESI exam was unfairly graded but she adjusted after complaints. Exams weren't too bad, she gave a study guide. Lots of lecture, got pretty boring. Overall the class is fine just not my fav

Pop quizzes - require you to be in class. Midterm was pretty easy, BUT we had a HESI exam over material we HAVE NOT EVEN LEARNED YET and was something that we couldn't study for... Class average was 60% and she said this was to be expected... yet made it worth 50 points. So unfair, class flipped out on her. Besides this, mediocre class.. LONG (3hr)

summary_comment: Professor Porembski is highly regarded for her dedication and effectiveness in teaching pharmacology, despite the challenging nature of the subject. Students appreciate her thorough lectures, which are supplemented by a flipped classroom approach that allows for flexible learning. While some find the workload demanding, especially with the need to prepare before in-person classes, they commend her fairness, availability, and genuine care for their success.

Ratings.comment: I LOVED her. Pharm is a hard class but she did do her best to make it easier. My advice, charts are your best friends. Organization is key. Tests are not to bad but weekly quizzes keep you accountable for your knowledge of material. You have to watch about 1-2 hours of pre recorded material before the 3  hour in person class WHICH SUCKS.

She isn't very clear with her exams. I never know what to study for her exams and I feel like some of the questions are trying to trick us. She is quite lecture-heavy but they are jammed-packed with helpful information. The flipped classroom is not a good setup for this course. It is quite hard to keep up alongside my other flipped classrooms.

Pharmacology is a HARD class but Professor Porembski worked incredibly hard to make sure we learned the material. We had to listen to lectures before class which I loved (pause, rewind, relisten) and in class we got to apply the material to the real world. She is very fair, very kind, incredibly caring, quick to answer emails & give extra help!
There is no textbook for this class so the lectures are very important. Professor Porembski is very intelligent and helps emphasize the content that will be important for quizzes and exams.

She was always available to answer questions during lab, explained this really well, and it was so invested in my success both in this class and as a future nurse. I could tell she was smart and really knew her stuff too! I learned so much.

SEI.Class Name: Evolving Concepts in Leadership and Management

summary_comment: Brooke is highly regarded as an exceptional professor, known for her caring nature and effective teaching methods. Students praise her clear and concise lectures, supportive approach, and fair exams. Her dedication to her students' success is evident, making the course manageable and enjoyable despite its complexity.

Ratings.comment: N/A
Brooke is a wonderful professor and person. She has great and concise lectures and exams!
I have never had such a kind professor. She cares so much about the wellness and success of her students. This course was very manageable and I learned so much!

Brooke really cares about us, as nursing students, and will do everything in her ability help us learn. I had her for both patho and pharm, and can truly say that she is a great lecturer and wants us to learn the material even if it is complex.

Brooke has to be the sweetest professor I've ever had. She has made it clear since the beginning of the semester that she is here for us and that she wants to see us succeed. She made this slightly difficult course pretty easy to pass, as long as you put in the work. She makes sure you receive the maximum amount of help. Would def take her again!!

She always tells us she is new to teaching and new to the course content. I prefer a professor who at least someone knows what they are doing (or at least pretends). She's very nice, easy, and tells us exactly what we will be tested on. I'm glad I got an A but I didn't actually learn very much and it's negatively impacting this semester.

Brooke is the nicest professor I've had! She genuinely cares so much about all of her students and makes the class enjoyable. She even brought candy on Halloween. The exams are made to not trick us and are straightforward. You have to study a good amount and know the information, but the exams are very fair. The content was also really interesting.
Brooke is such a great professor and she is always looking to help her students. Super nice and prepared well for her lectures. Gives us a clear outline for exams. Dont need to read. Do the prepUs!

Prof Rengers is amazing. She is very thorough with her content and gives very in-depth explanations. If she does not know the answer to a question she will take the time to find that answer for you. I had her for both pharm and patho and she was amazing in both classes.

Dr. Rengers was amazing! She clearly cares about her students and has one of the kindest dispositions ever. She prepared us well for exams. Weekly quizzes keep you accountable for studying, and besides that there are only some group assignments to do outside of class. Overall, loved her and am so excited that she is teaching pharm next semester!

Brooke is one of the best professors I have had so far. She is so nice and she prepares you so well for tests. She truly cares for her students and wants you to succeed. I am so excited to have her again for Pharmacology.

SEI.Class Name: Epidemiology Concepts in Nursing and Global Healthcare

summary_comment: Christine is a dedicated and passionate professor who expects her students to put in effort but provides ample resources to support them. She prepares her students well, making her final exam one of the easier ones in the junior year. While some students find her teaching methods challenging and inefficient with long class times, others appreciate her care and passion for teaching, noting that participation in end-of-semester activities can significantly help with the final exam.

Ratings.comment: Christine is a passionate teacher. You need to put in effort, but if you commit and use the resources, you'll do well. She uploads her lectures after class now. Her final was the easiest of my junior year because she prepares her students well. As a clinical instructor, she's tough but makes you a better student!
Great teacher. Passionate and wants students to learn.

Makes the class way more than it needs to be. Doesnt record lectures which would be VERY helpful. Every other professor ive had has always recorded lecture. Makes us do silly in class activities that are a waste of time. Class goes the full time 3 hours and 30 min which could easily be an hour and a half.

Christine is an awesome professor and really cares for her students! It is very apparent she is passionate about what she teaches! Just get to class, do the assignments (some questions taken for quizzes), and GO TO THE END OF SEMESTER KAHOOT! It will help you on the final significantly!
Grades all of the assignments and is very helpful when asking questions. Very picky about grammar and citations. Sometimes slow on grading discussion boards.

The professor was also noted for her poor memory of students' names and a lack of engagement during lectures. In another instance, while Molly was deemed a decent lecturer and made the coursework relatively easy, she was considered an unsupportive clinical instructor who failed to build relationships with students and was frequently absent from clinical sessions.

Ratings.comment: Dr. McAuley was a very kind professor and seemed very passionate about nursing. However, the lectures for this course were not very interesting, and I often dreaded going.
Long and boring lectures. Must read and know the material. Poor attention span of the teacher. She doesnt remember anyones names.

I had Molly, as both my professor and my peds clinical instructor. She was a decent lecturer and the class overall was easy. All the quizzes and final are online. However, she was a pretty absent clinical instructor and despite being with her for 7 weeks she never learned a single one of our names and was MIA half the clinical.

summary_comment: This professor is widely regarded as one of the worst instructors due to her unprofessionalism, loudness, and reliance on reading directly from PowerPoint slides without elaboration. Her teaching methods are described as confusing and difficult to follow, with students finding it easier to learn through self-study or textbooks.

Ratings.comment: The worst instructor ever, unprofessional, and loud. She reads straight from the PowerPoint. Difficult way of teaching. I will not recommend anyone to be in her class.

She obviously doesn't care about teaching. she uses other's slides and doesn't even bother changing the author's name to herself. Will quiz you on things she doesn't talk about in class. Hard to understand her in class.

She has a very convoluted way of thinking and you can hear it from her lectures. She makes it very difficult to understand. She just talks and talks and talks in her lecture. She talks very fast too. Just Google it or read the textbook. They are all better than her.

She is knowledgeable and has a funny personality. On the other hand, she did not reply to 2 emails and was not very clear about a few aspects of what she expected from the class which resulted in some tension with the students. summary_comment: Dr. Thomas excelled in making the subject matter accessible through effective breakdowns and multiple teaching methods, though the content was inherently time-consuming. Her approachability and kindness towards students were notable, contributing to an overall positive learning experience despite the challenging nature of the material.

Ratings.comment: Dr. Thomas was very nice to her students, however, the subject matter itself was very time consuming. I feel like she did a very good job of breaking down the material into different ways that allowed it to be understood, despite the difficult and time-consuming content.

summary_comment: The professor delivers a highly effective and accessible course that emphasizes engagement and timely submission of assignments for success. However, some students noted that the course content appeared to reflect the instructor's personal views more than established professional nursing standards, which were not clearly aligned with guidelines from The College of Nursing, The American Nurses Association, or The State Board of Nursing.

Ratings.comment: Cultural comp was a very eye-opening course. This class is not intended to be hard. As long as you put in the work, submit your assignments on time, and view the modules, you should get an A in the course! There is a long paper at the end so get a head start with that if possible.

Course goals, ideas and lectures seemed to be more heavily influenced by personal views than views espoused by The College of Nursing, The American Nurses Association or The State Board of Nursing. If values were taken directly from those groups, it was poorly communicated.

summary_comment: Dr. Balas is widely regarded as severely underqualified and ineffective, failing to engage with students or provide meaningful instruction. Students describe her lectures as unhelpful, with her reading verbatim from poorly prepared slides that contain errors and misinformation. The overall learning environment is described as negative and potentially harmful due to the inaccuracy of the information provided.

Ratings.comment: This professor doesnt actually teach at all. She reads off of slides that someone else has prepared, doesnt answer student questions, grades late, posts lectures late, and genuinely seems confused about the information shes teaching. I think she means well, but she often cracks jokes that belittle students. Overall negative learning environment.

Dr. Balas is severely underqualified to teach pathophys. She reads symptoms off a slide but cannot explain any actual patho. She is a danger to future patients and is an example of why NPs should not be given full practice authority. It's embarrassing that OSU allows this kind of education in their graduate nursing program. Utterly incompetent.

One word: HORRIBLE. Dr. Balas does such a disservice to the graduate program. She reads verbatim off of slides that are fraught with misspellings and misinformation. Dr. Balas does not appear to know the information, often mispronouncing words and contradicting the text. She is unorganized, unprepared, and unprofessional. Abysmal.

I think it is honestly unsafe for Dr. Balas to teach this course. She often gives incorrect information regarding topics that nurses NEED to know to do their job well. She does not explain anything--she reads verbatim off of her slides. Slides are confusing and unclear. She doesn't actually seem to know the information that she is teaching.

Professor only reads off of the slides and her slides are directly copied from the textbooks. She does not teach the material but rather, just reads the textbook to students during lectures. She is not helpful for questions and is demeaning towards students.
The worst! Deliberately trying to trick you on test while reads of her slides not giving you any info in lecture. Nightmare.

summary_comment: This professor assigns extensive reading but does not include time constraints on quizzes or tests, making it easy to refer back to the textbook. While her powerpoint presentations and online lectures are considered unhelpful by students, she is noted for being very supportive and responsive when students seek clarification.

Ratings.comment: Assigns many chapters from the book, however, none of her quizzes or tests are timed so flipping through the book to find answers is easy. Powerpoints are useless, don't bother using them or the online lectures. Couple group projects completed through discussion boards. She is very helpful when you ask questions.

summary_comment: Based on student comments, this professor is widely regarded as ineffective and detrimental to the learning experience. Students describe her as unorganized, uncompassionate, and poorly equipped to teach, with many finding her exams excessively difficult and her lectures confusing. Her teaching methods are considered harmful and demoralizing, with multiple students hoping she is never allowed to teach again.

Ratings.comment: Explains how to perform exams and is always there to answer question.  will work a student is needed.

WOWWWWW! I could not believe how horribly she ran our class! I have honestly never had a teacher like this before. I look down upon the OSU nursing department for putting someone like that in charge of teaching over 150 students. Horrible. Enough said. I hope no one else gets stuck with her.
I hope she never is allowed to teach again.

By far the WORST teacher I've ever had! For being a nurse, she sure has NO compassion. The notes were completely unorganized, and the exams were ridiculously hard. If you go to her for help, she will make you feel stupid.

okay were should i start number1.she's horrible.2.her notes weren't organized.3.she doesn't know how to teach.4.her test was unbelievable.5.you get tested on something you didnt learn.6.you will not know what to study for for the exam b/c she wont tell u.7.you will do a lot of guessing on the exam. man i can go on and on but it wont let me.good luc

This was the worst instructor I've had in the nursing school. I hope she's never allowed to teach 385 again. She has no idea what she is lecturing about and is very immature and condescending towards students.

summary_comment: Diane is highly regarded as an exceptional professor, known for her ability to explain and organize complex content effectively. While her classes are challenging and require significant effort, students consistently praise her dedication to teaching and her willingness to help. Despite initial intimidation, many find her supportive and caring once they engage more with her.

Ratings.comment: Awesome person, tough class

Diane is one of the best professors I've ever had at explaining and organizing class content. She was enjoyable, and you can tell she actually cares about teaching nursing students. It is for sure a difficult and stimulating class, but if you put in the work and go to class, she makes it possible to do well and actually learn a lot!

I had Diane for patho and that class was just all around hard but I love having her for pharm. She tries to make the subject fun and provides a lot of info and resources. Currently my best class. She sounds really harsh in her emails but she reaches out in person. Make sure you make yourself known early, it goes a long way
to me she was the nicest professor at OSU CON period. She cared about her patients and students

Diane is a great teacher.  She is intimidating at first but once you get to know her you will really like her.  She wants her students to do well and she is there to help.  The material is difficult so you need to study a ton, but she is always there to help.
Although the material is difficult and time consuming Sheets is there to help you master it and get an amazing grade. This class requires a fair amount of studying in order to do well.

Diane is extremely intimidating at first, but once you show interest in her course and make a student-teacher relationship with her, she's amazing. She goes above and beyond to help her students. Her tests are hard, but not too bad if you really study. You will be lucky to get her as a clinical instructor, you'll learn SO much from her.
Diane is an awesome teacher, a little intimidating at first, but once you get to know her you will love her (maybe). She knows her stuff and is will to answer any questions you may have.

She is an awesome person. Brilliant and funny. Too smart for her own good though. Unrealistic in her exam expectations. She was also my clinical instructor which was intimidating because she really keeps you on your toes, but very rewarding. I learned a ton from her.

My favorite teacher/clinical instructor. The exams for 385 were VERY straightforward, but the frustration is the amt of MATERIAL.  However, many people got A's. It's not her fault that there is so much info in 385, THIS IS NURSING, IT'S GONNA BE HARD, WE DON'T WANT JUST ANY IDIOT RUNNING AROUND BEING A NURSE. It's sink or swim -

She was very knowledgeable and overall an interesting lecturer. The material of the course is difficult though. Her testing isn't always consistent, but that could be the nature of the class. Overall it was difficult but I learned a lot from her.

I had her for 385.01 and she was very hard. You need to know every little detail plus some because the questions on her tests are asked NCLEX style. As you get used to taking these tests your grades will go up and study time will go down esp. once you take her with 301.3. Her tests are very fair in 301 and her style of teaching it is better.
Course packet from the underworld. Hate it. Class is fine otherwise- Diane is nice but that packet.....

She was not very thorough with her explaining. I felt she expected you to understand way too much prior to coming to class and then didn't explain well during class. She was very hard to follow and the class got long.
She was an amazing teacher and you could really tell that she has a passion for her students and the patients she cares for!

She definitely knows her stuff and can answer almost any question "those kids" throw at her... (You know the ones I'm talking about... the ones who think they're so smart and clever?) Lectures are very straight forward. Tests require that you figure out the "best answer" possible, much like the NCLEX.
Knew the material she was responsible to teach us. Always there when you needed extra help.

I have diff opinions of her, final was the easiest, other exams were fair, its hard to study for it because her answers are the 'BEST' answers, enjoyed going to her classes, made it fun, overall enjoyed teh class

I loved her class. She is by the book and follows the rules. but so much fun. Material was sometimes hard to work with and a little boring at times but she made it fun. if you study and pay attention come to class you will do fine!!

Diane is pushey!  She will let you know if you have asked a stupid question and will shove you out of the way if you are in her path.  As far as patient care in the hospital, she has very little compassion and is mostly about the facts and following the rules... good luck with this one!
Sista sheets was great. I had her as a clinical instructor and she is great. You just have to understand her humor and take the time to get to know her.
No Comments
No Comments
No Comments
No Comments

Some say Diane comes off condescending, arrogant, and close-minded (which is a valid observation). i think she has been a proficient nurse for so long that she forgets that we are beginners and need a more supportive relationship with her. her tests aren't great. too much material to draw from :(
Tough teacher, but great person.  One of the few professors who I felt really cared about how I did.    Definitely has her favorites.
Boring condescending ****
Extremely belittling, intimidating, and snooty. Very poor teaching style.

Diane definitly has her 'favorite students' that she advocates for. If you are not one of those students it's difficult to ask her questions. She picks very detailed questions and puts them on exmas. Topics she spent 30 seconds talking about in class. Don't bother trying to argue answers with her.

In addition to the last two comments, she picks the smallest detail from a 50 page chapter and expects you to  recall it for the test.  When this is then pointed out  to her, she feels the need to belittle you until and you stop bothering her.
I agree with the last comment.  In addition, she gets gradually more annoying and snooty as the year goes on.. and trust me, she will make herself known in 301.01, 301.02, AND 301.03.

Likes to make students feel intimidated and loves to make students feel stupid when they ask questions or don't know an answer to a question in clinical.  As a lecturer, she likes to add little annoying comments to the class about how they are behaving
No Comments

summary_comment: This professor is highly regarded for her friendliness and enthusiasm, with many students praising her clear and organized teaching style and willingness to help. However, her class has been noted as becoming significantly more challenging, particularly in its final stages, and some students have found her approach to be condescending or overly simplistic. Overall, while there are mixed opinions on the difficulty level, her positive demeanor and strong knowledge of the subject matter are consistently highlighted.

Ratings.comment: I really liked her in the fall semester when I had her she was really sweet and funny. This semester her class is incredibly difficult. You immediately go from kinda NCLEX style questions but not really to full on NCLEX style. Normally an A student, not with her class. Whenever I go to her for help with NCLEX style she just refers me to a book.
she's SOOO sweet and i loved having her as a teacher!! Shes willing to help and wants her students to do well.  Best teacher
Enjoyed class, most exam questions are fair but a few just seem to come from nowhere.

The notes are very clear and organized, but other than that I did not enjoy the class. She talks to us like we are children, which makes sense because she was a pediatric nurse. If you ask questions, she can make you feel dumb. If you point out that she made a mistake in the notes, she gets very mad.
lovely lady! :)
great teacher! very friendly and enthusiastic about what she is teaching. she is very helpful!
The best teacher. She is very clear and extremily nice. She deserve to teach 301 in all three quarters. She knows her subject very well and she loves what she is doing.
She was very helpful and very enthusiastic! I loved her as a teacher and clinical instructor. She realy loves what she does!
This teacher is very helpful and very clean on her lectures. The students that gave 1s ands dont know what they are talking about. Highly recommend this teacher
Nice Lady, was a little hard at times.
No Comments
No Comments

You learn alot from Cindy. She doesn't give much direction on what to study for quizzes, but if you know case study material you will do ok on tests. As for being fair, all I can say is she likes to tell you material won't be on the test. She tells you to cross off material in your notes during class, yet it appears on at least 3 final Q's. Ok?

Cindy is probally one of the truly nicest people i've ever met. Her lectures are interesting if you are truly interested in nursing and as a clinical instructor she is great. She will guide you along just enough and has great knowledge to pass on to her students. Learn as much as you can from this woman and be thankful to work with her.

Cindy is really unfare and arrogant. She will pick the most obscure things to put on the exam, and all of the options on the multiple test questions are correct. However, the only one correct answer is the one she feels like when she's writing the exam. The whole class can argue with her about her poorly written questions, but she won't back down.
No Comments

summary_comment: This professor is known for being a strict grader and has difficulty with clear communication, often resulting in poorly edited messages and hard-to-read lecture materials. Students find the class challenging and monotonous, with assignments perceived as tedious and the material dry. Additionally, many describe the professor as boring and confusing in their delivery.

Ratings.comment: She's a very tough grader.  Even if you pay close attention to the requirements for each assignment, she will take off points. Her communications with the class are poorly edited. The lecture materials can be hard to read at times because there are many grammatical errors, missing words, etc.   Try to keep your composure and just get through.

This is the worst class ever.  The papers are ridiculously trite and time consuming.  Discussion boards = busy work.  The readings are dry.  And all you learn about it critical thinking, something anyone with a pulse can understand and apply.
she's so BORING! she's also very strange in her mannerisms and can be very unclear.

summary_comment: Janet is an experienced and knowledgeable clinical instructor who engages students with compelling stories from her nursing career. She is highly organized, deeply committed to her students' well-being, and exceptionally skilled at teaching.

Ratings.comment: Has a ton of experience in the field. Very interesting and informative "stories" from her years of nursing. Organized. Awesome teacher.
Janet is a very good clinical instructor. She is extremely helpful and knows her stuff. She always has her students best interest in mind. AWESOME!

summary_comment: The professor is highly regarded for her comprehensive lecture slides and effective highlighting of key information during her sessions. Despite the challenging nature of the course, students find her approachable and dedicated, though some note that her explanations can sometimes be confusing due to contradictions. Participation is encouraged and can impact grades, and while the material is demanding, consistent attendance and focused studying can lead to success.

Ratings.comment: She provides all necessary information in the lecture slides, but she highlights the "need to know" information during her lectures

She is an awesome professor (probably one of the best for first year nursing). The information is challenging, just make sure you go to class and pay attention. I never really read the book, BUT you do need it for the online quizzes! Lectures are recorded, but there is participation in class. Study the study guide and applications and youll be ok!

Patho is a tough class, but not impossible if you go to lecture and study as you go. Kim does her best to teach such a hard class and did a good job for it being her first year teaching all of the material on her own. Lectures are not mandatory but points are given for coming to class so it can affect your grade. Tests are not bad if you study well

Kim was not the best professor for such an important and hard class like Pathophysiology. She often contradicts herself in lecture, which leads to more confusion on the already difficult content. You get points for participation, so come to class. Lectures often run over or you have to finish listening to it online. She was the sweetest lady though

summary_comment: Dr. Neal is an outstanding instructor known for making complex material accessible and engaging, while maintaining high academic standards. Students find his classes both challenging and enjoyable, praising his approachability and effectiveness in teaching. While some classes were tough due to new material, overall, he is highly regarded as one of the best instructors in the College of Nursing at Ohio State.

Ratings.comment: Good teacher
Just an outstanding instructor. Very engaged and very approachable. Made the class very fun while we learned a lot.
Dr. Neal was an absolutely wonderful instructor -- one of the best in the College of Nursing at Ohio State.
Excellent teacher...make difficult material simple.
Took a while ago now--but remember that it was a tough class mostly because of so much new material. People complained at lot but simply needed to study more. Doable class if you put the time in.
bad
Kinda hard class but new material. Focused on essential material. Exams fair but hard.
No Comments
No Comments

I absolutley hated this class. Jeremy was not a help whatsoever! he does not know his material and when you ask him questions he has a blank look on his face. Multiple people are failing his class....it was very difficult and made me want to quit school. I would NOT reccomend this teacher!!!

summary_comment: The professor is highly regarded for her engaging teaching style and enjoyable class atmosphere, though her exams can be challenging due to their difficulty and focus on fundamental knowledge. Some students find her exams tough because they test on topics not explicitly covered in class, particularly priority nursing plans. Others praise her warmth and humor, describing her as an exceptional teacher.

Ratings.comment: Exams are somewhat difficult because she doesn't teach you some of things she tests you on. She is judgmental if you don't know your basic nursing knowledge from the first year. The hardest questions are the priority nursing plan ones.
Such an amazing person and teacher. Her exams are all online! I actually had fun going to class. She tells the funniest stories! LOVE HER

summary_comment: The professor is generally well-regarded, with some students finding her engaging and entertaining, while others find her class and workload demanding. Reviews are mixed, with one student praising her as "excellent" and another describing her as "useless," highlighting significant differences in perception. Overall, her teaching style is appreciated for making complex topics more accessible, though some find the workload excessive.

Ratings.comment: She is funny and laid back. Although I don't quite care for research I can see how this class is beneficial.
Useless class. Too bad its required. She is so scatterbrained its ridiculous. The paper requirements were stupid. She requires way too much work for the credit hours you get.
Excellent prof!

She's a good teacher. her examples make the subject matter easier to learn. very entertaining. NEVER call her by Vicki; she'll sender you an email telling her to address her by Dr.VonSadovsky in the future. geez. anyhow, her 1st exam is hard, but she uses the same questions on all of the proceeding exams, making it easier to earn an A.

summary_comment: The professor is known for challenging quizzes with tricky questions that do not aid in learning, requiring students to rely heavily on their notes. Despite this, she offers valuable insights through interesting stories and has a sense of humor, though some find the final exam intimidating.

Ratings.comment: Quizzes have trick questions that don't help me learn or understand.
Study your notes for the quizzes.  Buy her published patho book.  The final was a little scary.  She's got some interesting stories to share and a sense of humor.
No Comments

summary_comment: The professor is highly regarded for her expertise and engaging teaching style in women's health and midwifery, making her one of the best instructors in these fields. Despite mixed feedback, many students praise her deep knowledge, fairness, and ability to inspire exceptional clinical practice. Some note that her teaching methods can be repetitive, while others appreciate her approachable nature and dedication to student success.

Ratings.comment: The best teacher in women health and midwifery.  She was treated very unfairly but she gave each and every student something great when it came to OB and Midwifery to take away with you and to make you an extra ordinary clinician.  She knew her stuff and had total command of the class room.A great lost to OSU I am glad that I was exposed to her!!!
uninterested in helping students. really only wanted to have her life and could care less about the students.

Outstanding instructor and really know her OB topics.  She demands that you work at your full potential and sheis a extremely fair and caring instructor.  The person who rated her down and said all we did was listen to the same stories over is a big liar and thought she knew more than the teacher. I learned lots from this teacher.Take her class
This is the only nursing class with a professor that is understanding enough not to overload you and presents the material in a way that will keep you engaged. TAKE HER CLASS!!
Such a great lady and a fun class! Seriously, it's the only nursing class I've ever felt relaxed in. If she's teaching a class, you should definitely take it!
Outstanding teacher with a true heart for teaching.  Best course I took in 3 years

Easy Class. Coursework did not follow any sort of logical flow. We sat in lecture for 3 hours, listening to the same story over and over. Professor very unhelpful with different situations. Gives out unexcused absenses for funerals and medical excuses. Nice Lady outside of class however her teaching is a bit misguided
Down to earth and knows her stuff, she has not forgotten what it is like to be a student.  Very knowledgable of subject matter and makes learn interesting and fun

Marsha is so great. If you ever see that she's teaching 440, then take her! i think she only teaches in the winter, otherwise she only teaches grad students. she's all about making things easy for her which means really easy on us.

summary_comment: The professor is highly regarded for her knowledge and dedication to her material, though some find her classes challenging due to their depth. Students appreciate her fairness, helpfulness, and efforts to make learning engaging, with multiple ways to earn extra credit. Her teaching style is effective, particularly for those in the nursing program, as she prepares students well for real-world applications.

Ratings.comment: Good teacher

Pretty easy classes (385.02 &385.03)compared to 385.01. An A is manageable as long as you keep up with your studying for the weekly quizzes. There are also many ways to obtain participation points that can eventually count as extra credit in the end. Wendy is very knowledgeable...too bad she won't be teaching any longer, especially 385.

She is an intelligent, passionate professor, very devoted to her material. However, shes one of those people who is so smart she talks over your head, digging to deep in the material. unrealistic expectations for the amount of studying she thinks we do, but overall I respect her and learned alot. Just be prepared to strain the brain!

WOOOOOOOOOO I love this woman!!! It is freaking hard being in the Nursing program and having a teacher who tested you on what you would encounter on the job, what medications/interventions would be relevant to your working experience was a gift from God!! This woman is a savant also.
She was very helpful and fair. She was really willling to make sure you knew the info as well as make class fun! I really liked her class and all the opportunities she gave to improve your grade!

summary_comment: The professor is highly approachable and genuinely interested in engaging with students, though the class material can be枯燥乏味，考试还算过得去。总体而言，她是一位不错的教师。

Ratings.comment: very approachable prof; interested in working with students
The class was boring but she was a nice teacher. You could take your final with a partner. Exams were ok.

summary_comment: This professor has a poor reputation for consistent and fair grading, often setting low expectations early in the semester and adhering to them rigidly, regardless of student performance. Her grading style is described as nitpicky and unfair, with vague and misleading feedback that does not accurately reflect students' actual performance. Students generally advise avoiding her if possible due to these issues.

Ratings.comment: Nitpicking is her grading style. There are great teachers who grade tough to bring the best out in you. She is anything but that. It's like she set your grade in HER mind early in the semester and makes sure you get that grade no matter how hard you try. Gives scratchy video feedback saying u did great when she's failing you. Stay away if you can.

summary_comment: The professor delivers high-quality, inspirational lectures in an online course format. While prior knowledge of anatomy and physiotherapy is recommended, it is still possible to perform well without them. The course relies heavily on the textbook, which is easy to understand, though students find the Panapto lectures challenging and recommend asking questions when confused.

Ratings.comment: Wonderful class with inspirational lectures.

Online course. Not required, it is rec that you have anatomy & physio before taking class. I did not have these & it is possible to get a good grade. The text is used exclusively for tests & is easy to understand. A lot of reading but her study guides help narrow down info. Panapto lectures diff to understand vs. book. Must ask ques. if confused!

summary_comment: Dr. Ice excelled as a clinical instructor, adeptly balancing challenge and support to help students reach their full potential. Her teaching approach was both rigorous and empathetic, making her not only a highly effective instructor but also a role model for aspiring nurses.

Ratings.comment: Dr. Ice was my Clinical Instructor for this course. She knew exactly how and when to push a student to be their best or give a student a break because they were having a hard day. She was a fantastic instructor and is the type of nurse that I aspire to be one day.

summary_comment: Hollie is an outstanding professor known for her engaging and humorous teaching style, which simplifies complex nursing assessment skills. She is highly praised for her care, encouragement, and clarity in lectures, as well as her relatable real-life stories that enhance the learning experience.

Ratings.comment: Hollie is a great professor. Very funny and makes learning basic nursing assessment skills very easy. Lots of great stories about her nursing career that make going to class worth it. Material is very easy, but go to or listen to lectures (PPTs are fill in the blank and you get the answers from listening to lectures)

Hollie is fantastic. She is so caring and so encouraging. She is extremely helpful and very clear in lecture on the important points. I loved her stories and her real-life applications! You will love taking this class with her!
